snippet: The new exchanges between Israel and elements in Gaza marred an agreement to extend a cease-fire for another five days.
abstract: Palestinian leaders say that in last moments before expiration of cease-fire with Israel in Gaza, two sides have agreed to hold their fire for an additional five days to continue talks about a more durable truce; exchange of rockets and missiles, however, cast immediate doubt about whether it would even last until dawn.

byline.original: By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK and JODI RUDOREN
byline.contributor: David D. Kirkpatrick reported from Cairo, and Jodi Rudoren from Gaza. Merna Thomas contributed reporting from Cairo, Isabel Kershner from Jerusalem, and Fares Akram from Gaza.

lead_paragraph: The new exchanges between Israel and elements in Gaza marred an agreement to extend a cease-fire for another five days.

headline.main: Rocket Fire Casts Doubt on Truce in Gaza
headline.print_headline: Rocket Fire Casts Doubt on Truce in Gaza
